TLR2 is involved in recognition of peptidoglycan from gram-positive bacteria, bacterial lipoproteins, mycoplasma lipoprotein and mycobacterial products.It is expressed constitutively on macrophages, dendritic cells, and B cells. In some other cell types, like the epithelial cells i t can be induced .

The Molecular Pattern receptor Toll-like Receptor 4 is involved in recognition of Bacterial Lipopolysaccharides (LPS). LPS is assembled within diverse Gram-negative bacteria and is a component of the bacterial cell wall. It is a potent activator of the innate immune response in humans. In macrophages, lipid A (a form of LPS) activation of TLR4 triggers the biosynthesis of diverse mediators of inflammation, for eg TNF-alpha and IL1-beta, and activates the production of costimulatory molecules required for the adaptive immune response.

TLR5 is the receptor for flagellin, the protein that forms bacterial flagella. TLR5 is expressed on epithelial cells as well as on macrophages and dendritic cells. Expression of TLR5 on intestinal epithelium is polarized such that TLR5 is expressed only on the basolateral side of the cell.
Flagellin is a protein and is the principal component of bacterial flagellum

TLR2 agonist Pam3csk4, is a synthetic tripalmitoylated lipopeptide that mimicks the acylated amino terminus of bacterial lipoproteins

Dectin-1 agonist Curdlan, is a high molecular weight polymer of glucose. Curdlan consists of -(1,3)-linked glucose residues. It is produced by non pathogenic bacteria such as Agrobacterium biobar and also by some pathogenic bacteria such as Alcaligenes faecalis.
Nod1 recognizes peptidoglycan (PGN)-related molecules containing the amino acid meso-diaminopimelic acid (meso-DAP) that are produced by most Gram-negative and certain Gram-positive bacteria.
Nod2 is activated by muramyl dipeptide (MDP), which is a conserved structure in all types of peptidoglycan (PGN).
